segments.text: Your sense of contribution to the community is kind of rewarding, but basically it's just a lot of confidence-building maneuvers, because that's what we call things we did in the airplanes when you learn to fly, and especially in jet fighters.
But it was confidence-building activities

and leadership activities and you learn how to work with people and how to motivate people and I learned early on that one of the best ways to motivate people is just set a good example and be a good example and most time people will follow and then you don't have to
use more persuasive means of leadership if you don't have to.
And besides, if you have to use too much persuasion and motivation, a lot of times if you're in a voluntary type activity, you just turn to somebody else.
And if somebody's not pulling their share or making promises that they don't keep or don't fulfill, you just quit depending on them and associate with people you can depend on.
Let's go to academics.
Do you remember how you registered for the first time?
How'd you get into it?
How did they know what classes for you to get that first semester?
It seems like my first semester this year
It seemed like we went over to Sabisa Dining Hall and you stood in lines at different tables representing the different departments and the different courses within the departments.
You consulted with an academic advisor, and you had a card that you went through and filled out as you confirmed your different classes.
And I don't remember much about the details other than that first semester was fairly easy because there were so many core classes and basic classes that you had to take.
And it was just a matter of going through.
And yours was engineering?
Right.
It was engineering for the first two years, right.
Do you remember some of those first semester classes?

I remember that in one of the English classes I tested out of one of the first composition and rhetoric classes one of the basic ones and moved to an advanced class and in one of the mathematics classes I tested out of
one of the basic ones and got to start to tell you I had a pretty good academic background in Conroe.
And English and math were two of the classes where I tested out of the first semester of the first courses.
even though the classes I took were maybe a little more challenging than some of my contemporaries did, I was pretty well prepared for it and didn't have any real problems.
I never was a straight A student, but my, I believe it was my second freshman semester, and then two other of my nine semesters, I made distinguished student.
But so I was maybe a little above average, but not real high academically.
I always had to study quite a bit.
Things don't always come real easily.
I don't have photographic memory.
I don't have a real high IQ.
I think it measured somewhere, I don't remember, somewhere between 125 and 130.

I always had to study, had to do a lot of homework, and I found that if I did and if I was very methodical in the way I organized my studies and my note taking and kept up with my reading and so forth, that I could do okay.
Where did you do that study?

Mostly in my dorm room, but sometimes if there were activities and I knew that there were some turmoil or something going on in the dorm that would be distracting, I'd go to the library or maybe to the MSC.
Did you have special little places you found in those two?
Yeah, in the library, a lot of times you'd be okay just in one of the big public study desks.

but then later on when you were really in a crunch and really had to concentrate there were little cubicles up in the stacks where you could you could check out a number of books and you didn't have to check them out you could just get the books off the stacks once you learn the Dewey Decimal System and how to find them you could get the books you wanted you might have eight or ten books on a shelf above the little cubicle and you could sit there and then as you needed references or bibliography or something you could
pull them out of the books and you could sit there and write a term paper and then you didn't even have to complete it in that sitting.

You could leave it and then just put a note on the desk occupied and put your name on it and nobody would bother it and then I think there was a time limit of two or three weeks or something like that.
If you hadn't finished your paper then you might come back and find that your books had been put back

on the shelves in the stacks, and you'd have to go back and get them, put them back out, but most of the time when you got back there, your books were still right there, and so you'd just bring your notebook or your papers and continue where you left off.
That was a real good system.
If you were under stress or you just needed to get away, sometimes you could use that as an excuse and just go up there and put your head on the desk and take a nap.
Where in the MSC did you study?

down in the student programs areas, well sometimes there were meeting rooms that were unoccupied and unlocked that you could get into or even if they were locked, if you asked somebody, a lot of times, especially since I was known as an active participant and a committee member, you could get a key or get somebody to unlock one for you and then you just lock it when you left.
Did you have early on some classes and or instructors that were meaningful to you later?
Let's see.
I'm trying to remember who taught the, there was one of the classes called

and effective discourse, and I'm trying to remember who taught that, but that was one of my favorites, not only because it taught methodical logic, taught the difference between inductive and deductive, or subjective and objective reasoning,

And that's where I learned to appreciate the search for truth and the distinction between learning for the sake of wisdom and learning for the sake of manipulating the system where you learn the difference between truth and propaganda.

And whereas in an academic situation, the classic reason for a debate is for two sides to vigorously explore the pros and cons, with the outcome being to discover truths and fundamental principles of life that everybody can live by and help everybody improve themselves, in authoritarian systems,

the purpose of a debate is for one person to annihilate their opponent and truth matters very little and that became reinforced to me and became very important to me a little bit later in life when I had another little experience where I had to deal with propaganda

from a position of weakness for a number of years and yet that class helped sustain me considerably and that class especially combined with my Judeo-Christian background I was a born-again Christian Southern Baptist I'd probably be what a lot of the PC crowd call a fundamentalist
nowadays but evangelical Christian made a profession of faith when I was 10, 11, 12 years old and had always lived by that.
That coupled with everything I knew about our founding fathers and the way that United States of America was founded, history, government, politics, political science,
All of that made eminent sense to me when you look at truth, the truth, whole truth, and nothing but the truth, and then what Jesus said, he's the truth, the way, and the life.
To me, truth trumps everything.
Did those A&M semesters, did they reinforce all those ideas?
Well, they helped.
help develop them and reinforce them.
I think a lot of the reinforcement came later.
I think that was part of the developmental period and learning that and learning to appreciate that in a way that a lot of my adult contemporaries still don't seem to appreciate.
As an engineering major, were there some key engineering and or math science courses that you recall?

No just all of them helped reinforce the idea that there is order in the universe and I know as you get into really higher levels there is the chaos theory and some of that but that's way out on the fringes when you're pressing the edges of the envelope of knowledge and science and so forth but from the fundamental standpoint
There is order in the universe and I think the same creator that created spiritual laws and religious laws and interpersonal relationship guidelines also created
the laws of nature that affect science, mathematics, medicine, chemistry, all of those things.
And without order and predictability, society could never progress.
And I think it was the Renaissance and the Reformation that brought us out of the Dark Ages, where in the terms of human evolution, where

people began to realize although it took many more generations to really bring it to fruition that just because a dictator or an authoritarian or an elite group or an aristocratic family or something had power and could dictate what the rules and what the mores and things were going to be didn't necessarily mean they were right.
and that scientists and academicians could find truth and folks like Michelangelo and Dante even though they might be unpopular or outcast or a prize in their own time they knew truth and knew how to

to express it and fortunately in many cases we have the record of what they thought even when it was a minority opinion at the time or unpopular or might even get them persecuted like Martin Luther's theses.
You know history proved that they were right and truth prevailed even though the ruling authorities at the time
not only didn't go along with it, didn't like it, in some cases persecuted and martyred the people for it.
For you and your buddies, what did you all think were the unwritten rules about class attendance and class behavior and so forth?
Most of that was set by each individual instructor and some of them made it very clear that you would be there for every class and for every class you missed
if it was unexcused or if you didn't come by and make amends or apologize or offer the reason for it, a valid reason, that that was half a letter grade.
Did you do it regularly?
Yes, I did.
Not only because it was demanded.
I expected it of myself.
I just don't think you can keep up
in a fast-moving environment.

And like I said, I'm not a whiz kid that can cut five or six classes and then cram for an exam the night before or maybe listen to a few notes or maybe scan a CliffsNotes the night before a test and still ace it.
I can't do that.
I have to... What about, were there ever any pranks in class?
Did y'all, y'all didn't...
Not any that stand out.
There may have been some occasionally.
I would like to go back to that one.
This was significant to me, that class on logic and effective discourse.
When I went in to take the final exam, it was a two or three part exam.
And in fact, I think
One of the parts was even before the final exam day.
So when we came in there was a one part had already been turned in.
There was another part that was done the first hour and another part that was done the second hour and then the third hour was where you could finish up anything you wanted and turn it in.
Well at the end of the first hour
I turned my paper in, and it was more of a true-false type, a quick one.
And then the next one was a series of essays.
And so I turned it in, and the prof, about 20 minutes into the next session, he said, Mr. Ray, he said, you've done well enough that if you leave right now, you'll get a B in the class.
And I said, how strong will it be?
Is it close enough that if I do well on this last one, I can get an A?
And he thought for a minute.
He wasn't expecting that.
He thought for a minute, and he said, it's possible.
So I stayed that third and finished those essays and turned them in and I did get an A in the class.

And I don't know if my work was really that good or not but just the fact that I had turned down that opportunity to quit and take what I had to try to work for an A signaled to him that I was interested in it and I guess I did well enough on that that he gave me an A in it anyway.
So you and your buddies went to class regularly.
How many hours did you normally take per semester?
In fact, I think 18 was more the norm, and occasionally 19 or 20.
And I think the lightest load I ever had, excluding my last semester, in which case I took 15 or 16.
But I think prior to that, of the first eight semesters, I think I had one that had 17.
And all the others were 18 or more.
You know that 12 is now considered by most students to be a... And when I see that and I thought, oh my goodness, this...
This trend toward social promotion and feel good promotions and artificial self-esteem is really getting out of hand.
I really worry about the future of our civilization if this trend continues because if you don't have high standards and maintain them and work toward them,
you're not prepared to face life.

And I think it's a huge mistake among the educational communities and the teachers' unions and the educational curriculum directors and all of these folks that have been preaching situational ethics and moral relativism and all of that other stuff.
They're really undermining the foundations of our civilization.
I really feel strongly about that, but I'm not really sure what I can do about it other than
mention it as often as I can, and as a matter of fact, those kind of distinctions is what caused our marriage to break up.
You never thought about dropping out of A&M, transferring.
When that first year was over, how did you feel it had gone?
I felt like it had gone very well.
I mean, there had been some ups and downs.
There had been some

little incidents in the dorm where I'd gotten crossways with some of my classmates over some of their activities and one of the times that one of the issues was porno flicks in the dormitory and I guess in a way I was a little bit naive and maybe a little bit prudish but at the same time there were some practical aspects of that is that
Once you let your mind wander over into those areas, it's very distracting to accomplishing serious goals and purposes in life.
That next year, was it better to be a sophomore?
Oh, absolutely.
So much, so much better.
Because now you could be in charge and there was much less harassment, although the responsibility was still...

Even if you had determined from the way you were treated as a fish that you were going to be more enlightened in your leadership, you still had to be really diligent because you didn't want the outfit to fall down.
Sometimes you had to be pretty tough on guys that were either slow learners
or indifferent to really a search for excellence and success and being the best you could be as an outfit and as an individual.
So sometimes you have to, some people only understand a harassing type motivation.
Most people, however, respond to leadership by example and will take instruction and correction the way it's intended.
What do you think that Fish, your sophomore year, thought about you as a sophomore?

I don't know, I never got water ballooned or babo bombed, and I've always had good relationships with the guys, not really close friendships or anything, but sometimes guys will write to me, especially when I came back from Vietnam, calls and letters.
You had a different roommate.
Right.
those undergraduate years, to whom did you turn for advice, if you needed particularly academic advice?
Well, first thing I was going to say, the advice in general.
I was still active in the First Baptist Church and College Station and the Baptist Student Union.
Cliff Harris was the director of the Baptist Student Union in those days.

the folks at Sunday school class teachers, I always felt like any time, especially any moral issues, like I went over and talked to a Sunday school teacher who referred me to the pastor who at that time was Cecil Sherman.
And I guess this was my sophomore year, concerning the porno flicks and some things that were going on in the dorm that I didn't like.
And I went over and talked to him about how you stand up for what's right, but at the same time not break your relationships with your outfit and your classmates and your squadron mates and so forth.
And so that was a very helpful outlet.
Academically, Dean Ransdell was one of our squadron advisors.
And in engineering, there was a guy who had either an injured or withered arm.
Crawford?

I think Crawford later on became was a dean but at that time he was a I guess a professor and was an academic advisor so you know when if you if you felt like you were in trouble and weren't sure whether you're going to make it through without getting an F or D in the class sometimes you could go and and sometimes he could
contact the prof and say well you know is this guy just not trying or is he is it a little too difficult or and sometimes they can maybe could recommend maybe some extra sessions.
I never got something for nothing and I'm glad I didn't because I think that that sets up real bad habits for the future.
Were there supposedly some easy courses then where everybody made a high grade?
Oh, the physical education.
Some folks claim that the military science courses were cush courses, as they called them.
And there were some that had a reputation that if you felt like you wanted one or needed one to get your GPA up, you could take it.
And I had heard about those, but I don't think I was ever tempted to sign up for one like that.
What about at the other extreme?
Were there some courses that everybody thought it was real tough?
Yeah, there was chemistry.
There were several chemistry classes.
There were some calculus classes.
But here again, I figured that if they're tough, that means that it's important to know the stuff, and you've got to know it.
If you're not willing to put that effort into it, if you don't really like it,
then you better find another profession.
And then there were some instructors that were sometimes a little bit difficult to deal with.
And one that I didn't get along with very well at all was Ivy League Taylor.
A lot of folks liked him because he didn't really demand much day to day.
But he was very demanding on the tests.
And it was subtle, and it was difficult.
It was almost like you were being tricked into being lazy.
Because he'd just come in.
He'd sit on the desk and tell stories.
And the reading assignments were all kind of general and not very specific.
The learning objectives were not very specific.
And I like things to be structured.
I like to know in advance.
And it's not that I want somebody to teach the test to me, but I want somebody to structure some learning objectives so that I'll know as I go along whether I'm meeting these.
When something is just so...

nebulous that there's no form or no apparent function to it other than just remembering details of who did what to whom at a certain part in history if it doesn't have some significance to contributing to an idea or a principle or a growth or an evolution of a system of government or a system of philosophy

and if I think that something is going in that direction and the prof is not interested he's just interested in anecdotal details and a lot of details sometimes frivolous detail then I don't it's hard for me to relate to that and as a result of the
I think maybe I had two D's and one F in my whole career at A&M.
All the rest were mostly B's, occasional C's, and probably had more A's than I had C's.
But the two D's and the F were all in history classes.
Because history was, if it were not structured, it was just difficult for me to relate to it.

And then when I tried to put a structure to it, sometimes I was incorrect, or sometimes I had misinterpreted something, or maybe I was reaching a conclusion that maybe wasn't evident from that particular example in history.
So for some reason, I just didn't do well in the history courses, although I took enough of them that by the time toward the end of my sophomore year,

realized I didn't want to do engineering for the rest of my life and at that point I wasn't really sure what I wanted to do but I was being pulled maybe toward a pre-law degree maybe going to law school or maybe going into full-time Christian ministry so I knew

English and liberal arts would be a good background for either of those in fact the pre-law curriculum and the English curriculum when I went back and compared the text I was trying to decide what my new major would be they were pretty similar but I chose English as my new major because it offered the most undesignated electives so I had a lot of places to park a lot of my science and math and engineering courses
that otherwise I would lose if I had picked any other major.
And even at that, I had to go one extra semester because I had a lot of courses that just wouldn't transfer.
I had enough hours, but they weren't the right ones.
Major in English and a minor in history.
So I ended up with a minor in history in spite of the fact that some of my history courses didn't count for credit.
Were there some special teachers you had in that major?
that you now look back on and realize they were important?
I believe you're the only one that I can remember specifically.
I remember Ivy League Taylor, but I got a negative feeling about that.
And then there was one other history
Well, I can't remember the names, so apparently... What about over in English?
In English, Harrison Hurth, John Paul Abbott.
Those are the only two names that just off the top of my head...
I do remember one particular incident in...
Yeah.
